"Right." He pauses, thinking. "Well, he came to meet with me in the morning at the <strong>Skunkworks</strong> facility about the STORM program. Specifically, security. He thought an engineer named <strong>Vitruvius Pollio</strong> was acting suspiciously and might be a security risk. I didn't, and still don't, believe that to be true."

"Did he say anything interesting in the meeting?"

"Just what I told you. He had suspicions, but no evidence."

"What about the rest of his day?"

"That was the only meeting I had. That was the last time I - well, was going to say that was the last time I saw him that day, but I suppose it's the last time I saw him at all." He pauses. "I mean, I went to the wake. I saw his body. But that's different. Anyways, that's what I know. I've talked to folks afterwards, because of course his death was...well, it was a hot subject. Everybody was talking about it, but all that's secondhand. I wouldn't be able to put any stock in it."

"You mentioned the STORM program. Can you explain more?"

"It's a new short-range air defense program, designed to protect against a range of air-based threats, from loitering munitions to missiles and helicopters." He shrugs. "It's very advanced but I don't know how much you're interested in the technical details."

